Buyers beware! Do not purchase anything from Maingear!

I recently purchased the Maingear Element and was honestly disappointed by how many ways this device fell short. First off, the speakers are absolute garbage. They're downward firing and are hard to hear even at max volume, especially when it comes to dialogue. The second thing that disappointed was the build quality. The chassis is advertised as being made of a magnesium alloy, so you would expect it to be a similar quality to other laptops made with metal chassis, but it ends up feeling like cheap plastic. The coating that they put on this device is very matte, which ended up bothering me a lot more than expected. I honestly didn't even consider this being a possible issue for me because I own other devices with matte finishes, most of them just being matte plastic, which is actually really nice unlike the coating on this device. I was planning on ordering a dbrand skin before I decided to return the laptop. I would have preferred it been made out of aluminum with no coating, even if it meant the device being heavier. The keyboard takes some getting used to, but the layout is pretty good and the backlighting is excellent. The main issue I have with the keyboard is that there's no frame around each individual key, they just decided to make a massive cutout, which makes the keys to be less stable and causes you to accidentally press more than one key quite often. Finally, I started running into issues with the laptop freezing up on multiple occasions and this was in the first 2 weeks of owning it. On some occasions, the entire computer locked up with just a few chrome tabs open and nothing else, but sometimes the touchpad just stopped working randomly, yet the computer wasn't frozen. There is a way to disable the touchpad, but I tried disabling and enabling and that didn't change anything. The first two times this happened, I was still able to move the cursor with my Bluetooth mouse, but the third time I couldn't, though I could still scroll with the mouse for some reason, so not a Bluetooth problem. Aside from that issue, the wrist area got uncomfortably hot with just a few chrome tabs open and the fans at max speed.

Now onto why I said you shouldn't purchase anything from Maingear and not just this laptop. They claim to give have a 30 day money-back guarantee, but they charge a 20% restock fee, even if the device is defective. At $2400, that's $480 you're not getting back. This company would rather make customers front the cost of their mistakes than lose a single dollar in profit. They also have a lot of extras fees and conditions for how you return the device, including charging you for expensive tracking and shipping. If you don't package the device the exact way they want you to, they will charge you. If you don't have the original packaging, they will charge you. If you threw out the shipping box and foam, they want you to purchase it at a premium from them + shipping to you and back. For a laptop, that's $40 + shipping for two pieces off foam and a cardboard box. For a prebuilt desktop, that's as much as $289. Do not buy from this company, they do not care about consumers.

@c 0 z y I'm planning on purchasing the upcoming XPS 17. If you're looking for something that's great all around, you can't go wrong with an XPS device. The build quality is solid and actually feels premium, it is a bit heavier though because of that. And by heavier, I just mean it's not a thin and light. The two main reasons the upcoming XPS 17 is the ideal laptop for me is because of the 17 inch 4k screen in a laptop smaller than my current 15.6 inch Toshiba Satellite, the second being the RTX 2060 Max-Q Graphics card, which will handle most anything you can throw at it. The XPS 17 also has some major improvements over the previous iterations of the XPS 15 and 13, those being better speakers, a larger touch pad, and a vapor camber cooling solution. If you're looking for something more gaming centered, then the Razer Blade 15 is the best option, but is notorious for not being able to last more than 2 years and are over priced even if it was a long term device. After the Razer Blade, the Asus Zepherus G14 is supposedly pretty good, it has AMD's newest processor, but due to that, no thunderbolt 3. Also, the Gigabyte Arouros 17G. Though I can't speak for anything other than the XPS 17 and Razer Blade 15 since I've never had any experience with those brands before.

Ok, I'm in love. I've been wanting a Dell XPS 15 for years because it seemed like the best combination of performance and design, but the Maingear Element has just destroyed that for me. It's honestly perfect, and definitely better than the Dell XPS 15 in every way. I mean a 140hz IPS display and optical mechanical switches on a laptop as small as this?! That's crazy. Plus it comes with 1tb of nvme storage and an Nvidia 1660TI graphics card on the base model! The XPS 15 model that's comparable to that price point only has 256gb of nvme storage and a Nvidia 1650 Graphics card. Granted that specific XPS 15 model does have the 4K OLED display, which is what I kinda prefer, but having a high refresh rate monitor with an advertised 10 hour battery life is just as good, if not better. It's even outclassed by the ports, it adds two USB 3.1 Gen 2 ports, one type A and one type C, on top of the two USB 3.1 Gen 1 ports that the XPS 15 has. Personally I would probably go for the Stage 3 model though because of the 2tb nvme storage and Nvidia 2070 Max-Q graphics card. And since it comes with lifetime warranty and service, I'm paying a similar price I would be paying for similar specs on the XPS 15 with a 4 year warranty.
